caption: Located within Place Clemenceau, next to the Champs Élysées, stands this statue of the great french General, depicting him walking down the the famous boulevard, after the liberation of Paris, on the 26th of august 1944.

The Statue of General Charles de Gaulle is an imposing tribute to one of France's most iconic leaders. Its majestic presence in the city of Paris inspires respect and admiration.  A symbol of bravery and leadership that does not go unnoticed. Definitely a must-see for those looking to connect with the history and greatness of France!

Near the Champs-Élysées in Paris there is a statue of General Charles de Gaulle. During World War II, the German forces occupying Paris capitulated on August 25, 1944. The next day de Gaulle paraded on the Champs-Élysées.
This is a bronze statue of General Charles de Gaulle (later president). My impression was that he was slender and tall, but that's exactly what happened.
Charles de Gaulle is the monument to General Charles de Gaulle at Charles de Gaulle Airport on the Champs Elysées.

Statue located next to the Grand Palais, recognizable by its black and rather discreet silhouette although it represents one of the great men of France  It remains no less impressive, and its location could not be more symbolic.

Charles André Joseph Marie de Gaulle (French: Charles André Joseph Marie de Gaulle; November 22, 1890, Lille, France - November 9, 1970, Colombe-les-Deux-Eglises, Haute-Marne, Grand Est, France) - French military, political and statesman, Gen. During the Second World War it became a symbol of the French resistance. Founder and first President (1959-1969) of the Fifth Republic. Prime Minister (1958-1959) and Minister of Defense of France (1958-1959).

A silhouette recognizable among thousands, an approach from the history books, a true tribute to the general. Intelligently placed on a high base, it overlooks the square with its aura and is visible from afar. On this base, two famous sentences are inscribed: Côte de l'Étoile: "there is a twenty-year-old pact between the greatness of France and the freedom of the world" Côté de la Concorde: "Paris, Paris outraged, Paris broken, Paris martyred, but Paris liberated..." I really like this statue.

The statue of General de Gaulle is located near the Grand Palais. It was precisely in this symbolic place that in 1944 Winston Churchill and General de Gaulle placed a wreath of flowers at the foot of the statue of Clemenceau. The words spoken by General de Gaulle are engraved on the base of the statue.
